deeptools1diffbind

Cell paperhttps://www.cell.com/cell/fulltext/S0092-8674(19)30629-4

Requirement description

ChIP seq correlation, used to find cofactors.

Deeptools can achieve similar functionality, but it only selects one as the standard set as 1, and then compares the others with this standard. What I want is to cluster all the samples to see which ones are more similar, I cant choose which one as the standard. I used diffbind to achieve my goal and I want to find a better way. I really dont know how it was done in the literature, there is no description of the method at all.

Using this Cell paper< https://www.cell.com/cell/fulltext/S0092-8674 (19) Draw a correlation heatmap similar to this for the data of 30629-4>:

/ChIP-seqcorrelation

Application scenarios

Which regulatory proteins have binding sites that are more similar? Who is more similar to transcription factors after overexpression/knockdown? By calculating the correlation between ChIP seq data, clues can be found to infer the mechanism of action of transcription factors.

FigureYa104GEOmining

sort peak And change the file name to the name of factor

Observing the file names, it was found that the peak.bed files of this set of data all end with. narrowPeak, and the name of the factor is between GSM * and _ChIP.

Extract the name of the factor according to the naming rules of this set of data, and use it as the file name for the sorted peak.bed

for i in `ls *.narrowPeak`
do
x=${i/_ChIP_K562*.narrowPeak/} 
x=${x/GSM*_/}
sort $i -k1,1V -k2,2n -k3,3n > $x.bed
done

#Delete existing data
rm -rf *.narrowPeak

In practical operation, the name of your peak.bed file can be directly written as the name of the factor. Just run the following paragraph. If your peak.bed has already been sorted, you can skip this section and go directly to Start Drawing.

for i in `ls *.narrowPeak`
do
sort $i -k1,1V -k2,2n -k3,3n > $i
done

#Delete existing data
rm -rf *.narrowPeak

**Off topic: When publishing an article, the author will upload the sequencing data to the GEO/SRA database. In addition to the original fastq, bigwig (bw), or bedGraph files, most GEO also provides peak.bed files. You can directly download the peak.bed file or run it from scratch, call peak Generate peak.bed. You can refer to FigureYa107ChIPheatmap or FigureYa108RNAseqChIP.

Which data is more reliable? Recommend selecting data from articles with high impact factors, and refer to Figure Ya104 GEOmining for a quick way to query high scoring data.

Calculate correlation using intervene

Calculate the correlation coefficient between different peaks using Pearson or Spearman, etc. The example used is Pearson

intervene pairwise -i ./*.bed --filenames --htype color --corr --corrtype pearson

There are still many parameters in the interlayer, such as using the Jaccard index instead of calculating the fraction, which requires adding calculate Jaccard Htype {tribar, dendrogram, color, pie, circle, square, ellipse, number, shape} other graphic displays, including venn and upset, etc. The official tutorial provides detailed examples, please refer to the official tutorial:<https://intervene. readthedocs. io/en/latex/index. html>

**Output file: * * At the end of the run, an Intervene_ results folder will be generated in the current folder, containing three files:

-Intervene_ pairweise_frac.pdf, the diagram provided by Intervene - Intervene_pairwise_frac.R Draw the code for the image above. - Intervene_pairwise_frac_matrix.txt Correlation matrix, use it to redraw your favorite graph.

Draw with corrplot

If you feel that the above image is not cool enough and want more free space to express yourself, you can DIY draw with the file Intervene_pairwas_frac_matrix. txt. HCLUST Cluster Diagram:

#  | Read intersection matrix data from text file and convert to matrix format
intersection_matrix <- as.matrix(read.table("Intervene_results/Intervene_pairwise_frac_matrix.txt"))

# Pearson | Compute Pearson correlation coefficients between columns of the matrix
intersection_matrix <- cor(intersection_matrix, method="pearson")

# InterveneIntervene_pairwise_frac.R
# Intervene's built-in code, can be found in Intervene_pairwise_frac.R file
#pdf("Intervene_pairwise_frac.pdf", width=8, height=8)

# corrplot | Visualize correlation matrix using corrplot
corrplot(intersection_matrix, 
         method ="color",  #  | Use color to represent correlation coefficients
         title="Pairwise intersection-pearson correlation(Fraction of overlap)",  #  | Plot title
         tl.col="black", tl.cex=0.8,  #  | Set text label color and size
         is.corr = TRUE,  #  | Whether input is a correlation matrix
         diag=FALSE, addrect=1,  # 1 | Don't show diagonal, add 1 rectangle
         mar=c(0,0,2,1),  #  | Set margins
         rect.col = "black")  #  | Rectangle color

#invisible(dev.off())

# corrplot
# Leverage more corrplot parameters to enhance information visualization
# https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/corrplot/vignettes/corrplot-intro.html
pdf("Intervene_pairwise_frac_plus.pdf", width=8, height=8)  # PDF | Save enhanced plot as PDF

# | Custom color palette
cols <- brewer.pal(11,"Spectral")  # Spectral | Use Spectral color palette
# BrBG PiYG PRGn PuOr RdBu RdGy RdYlBu RdYlGn Spectral
# More color palettes: BrBG PiYG PRGn PuOr RdBu RdGy RdYlBu RdYlGn Spectral

#  | Enhanced visualization with more parameters
corrplot(intersection_matrix, 
         method ="color",  #  | Use color to represent correlation coefficients
         title="Pairwise intersection-pearson correlation(Fraction of overlap)",  #  | Plot title
         tl.col="black", tl.cex=0.8,  #  | Set text label color and size
         is.corr = TRUE,  #  | Whether input is a correlation matrix
         diag=FALSE,  #  | Don't show diagonal
         col = cols,  #  | Use custom color palette
         order = "hclust",  #  | Order variables by hierarchical clustering
         addrect = 4,  # 4 | Add 4 clustering rectangles
         mar=c(0,0,2,1),  #  | Set margins
         rect.col = "black")  #  | Rectangle color
invisible(dev.off())  # PDF | Close PDF device

pheatmap

corrplotpheatmap

Draw with pheatmap

The heatmap parameters of corrplot are rich, but it cannot draw trees. Lets use pheatmap to draw it

# pheatmap | Visualize correlation matrix using pheatmap
pheatmap(intersection_matrix, 
         cellwidth = 8,  #  | Width of each cell (pixels)
         cellheight = 8,  #  | Height of each cell (pixels)
         fontsize = 8,  #  | Font size for text
         
         #  | Custom color gradient: navy -> white -> firebrick
         color = colorRampPalette(c("navy", "white", "firebrick3"))(20),
         
         show_colnames = TRUE,  #  | Show column names
         show_rownames = TRUE,  #  | Show row names
         
         #  | Optional: Hide row clustering dendrogram
         # treeheight_row = "0",
         
         #  | Optional: Hide column clustering dendrogram
         # treeheight_col = "0",
         
         filename = "Intervene_pairwise_frac_tree.pdf",  #  | Output file name
         border_color = "NA")  #  | No border around cells
